properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Continued For The Churchill River From The Saskatchewan-Manitoba Border To Leaf Rapids Manitoba
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure’s Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning for the Churchill River from the Saskatchewan-Manitoba Border to Leaf Rapids Manitoba. If you are in the affected area, be watchful as local waterways are expected to rise quickly and may cause flooding. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Use caution when driving on all roads as road conditions may have changed. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by local authorities and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Stay tuned to local media for updates. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca
Expires: 2020-07-24T16:00:00-05:00

Area: Churchill River from the Saskatchewan-Manitoba Border to Leaf Rapids Manitoba

properties.Title: Update To Civil Emergency Alert Issued By Government Of Saskatchewan
properties.Summary:
Description: Update for the Civil Emergency Alert issued by the Government of Saskatchewan. The state of emergency in Saskatchewan remains in effect. UPDATE: for the week of July 20: the public is being reminded, as additional businesses, services and activities re-open during Phase 4.2, to always practice physical distancing of 2 metres when engaging with others. The Northwest Region remains restricted as Re-Open Saskatchewan proceeds. Go to the Saskatchewan COVID website listed in the instructions for a complete list of allowable services and activities in the Northwest Region. During all Phases of Re-Open Saskatchewan all public health orders, are to be followed and applied in all public and private gatherings.

properties.Title: Continued: Dam Overflow Alert Continued By Manitoba Infrastructure In The Areas Of Riverdale Municipality And Rm Of Whitehead
properties.Summary:
Description: Continued: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure is advising that risk of dam failure at the RIVERS RESERVOIR DAM continues at lower risk. Inspection results and lower water levels and flow have lowered the risk of imminent failure and evacuation orders for the inundation area can be lifted. Failure of the dam would result in extreme flooding and dangerous situations. Residents in the inundation zones should remain ready to evacuate on short notice if conditions change. Avoid water bodies, valleys, low lying areas and affected areas. Move to higher ground if required and avoid flooded areas. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca.
Expires: 2020-07-24T16:00:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2020-07-20T16:37:54-05:00, 05B3D8ED-F77A-4E80-EAE4-E3C5BF6A23ED
Area: Little Saskatchewan River in the Riverdale Municipality and RM of Whitehead.

properties.Title: Police Officer Stabbed In Bridgewater, Nova Scotia, Suspect At Large
properties.Summary:
Description: Man at large after stabbing a Bridgewater Police officer in Bridgewater, Nova Scotia. The weapon has not been recovered. He was last seen in wooded areas and back yards near the south edge of town approximately 4 hours ago. Police and RCMP have been actively searching for the suspect. He is wearing shorts with no shoes or shirt. If you see any suspicious persons or activity call the police.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High temperatures and humidity are expected over much of southern and western Nova Scotia through Wednesday. Time span: continuing into Wednesday evening. Maximum daytime temperatures: 27 to 30 degrees Celsius, except cooler along parts of the coast. Minimum nighttime temperatures: near 15 degrees Celsius. Locations: parts of mainland Nova Scotia. Remarks: Maximum temperatures on Wednesday will once again reach warning criteria over southern and western portions of the province. Although humidex values will be in the low 30s on Thursday, maximum temperatures are expected to reach only the mid 20s, and this warning is likely to be ended late Wednesday in these areas. Conditions will improve over eastern Nova Scotia, Kings County, and Hants County this evening, with cool overnight lows near 14 degrees giving some relief from the heat. This warning will be ended for these areas later this evening as temperatures begin to fall. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Information is provided on the Nova Scotia Department of Health and Wellness website at https://novascotia.ca/heat-related-illness/. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
Expires: 2020-07-22T10:56:58-00:00
